{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Yun et al. [65] reported that GGBFS replacements of 20%, 40%, and 50% reduced expansion by 5-10% and increased resistance to chemical attacks by up to 20%.",
    "Similarly, Moghadam et al. [66] found that GGBFS enhanced sulfate resistance by 10-15% and chloride resistance by 12-18% at replacement levels of 15%, 30%, and 45%.",
    "Zou et al. [67] noted improved chloride binding and sulfate resistance at a 30% replacement level.",
    "Chi et al. [68] demonstrated that GGBFS replacements of 20%, 40%, and 60% reduced water absorption by 10-15% and chloride permeability by 20-40%, with the best results at 40%.",
    "Additionally, Cleetus et al. [69] observed that a 20% GGBFS replacement Discover Civil Engineering (2024) 1:145 | https://doi.org/10.1007/s44290-024-00154-z Review enhanced the modulus of elasticity and flexural strength by 10-15%, while Cahyani and Rusdianto [70] found that increasing GGBFS content decreased porosity by 15-20%."
  ],
